<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-23T06:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-23T06:44:00-05:00" n="459" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/569: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wharton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-23T11:00:00-00:44">May 23,
                                    1942—11 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 1:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>161. In view of Liberian Government’s invitation to Germans to leave
                            country as reported in my 159, May 22,<note n="26" xml:id="d459fn26">
                                <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_421">p.
                                421</ref>.</note> increased submarine activity along Liberian coast
                            is anticipated. To combat such activity, as well as for other defense
                            purposes, I urgently request that initial flight of three light bombers
                            be stationed here as soon as practicable. In this connection I refer to
                            last paragraph of Colonel McBride’s telegram 56, March 6. Such a
                            detachment would also go far at this time to reassure Liberian
                            Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wharton</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>